2. LEGAL WARNING
🚨 UNAUTHORIZED ACCESS IS A CRIME
Accessing a computer, network, or device without authorization is illegal in most countries, including:

Country	Law	Maximum Penalty
USA	Computer Fraud and Abuse Act (CFAA)	Up to 10 years prison + fines
UK	Computer Misuse Act 1990	Up to 10 years prison
Canada	Criminal Code (Section 342.1)	Up to 10 years prison
Australia	Cybercrime Act 2001	Up to 10 years prison
Pakistan	Prevention of Electronic Crimes Act 2016	Up to 7 years prison + fines
India	Information Technology Act 2000	Up to 3 years prison + fines
EU	Directive 2013/40/EU	Up to 5 years prison
What constitutes unauthorized access?
Cracking WiFi passwords without the owner's permission

Attempting to log into someone's social media account

Using password wordlists on systems you don't own

Sharing cracked passwords with others

Any access without explicit written consent

💡 THE "JUST ASKING" DEFENSE DOESN'T WORK
"But I only wanted to see if I could do it!"
"I wasn't going to use the password for anything!"
"It's just for fun!"

Courts do not accept these excuses. The act of attempting unauthorized access is itself a crime – regardless of intent or whether you actually use the information.

