10. FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS
Q: Can I test my own WiFi?
A: Yes! Your own network is yours to test. This is a great way to learn.

Q: Can I test my friend's WiFi if they say "yes" verbally?
A: NO. Verbal permission is not enough. Get it in writing (email, text, or signed document). Without written proof, it's your word against theirs.

Q: What about public WiFi at cafes?
A: NO. You don't own it, and you don't have permission from the owner.

Q: I'm a security student – can I practice on my school's network?
A: Only with written permission from your instructor AND the network administrator. Otherwise, it's unauthorized access.

Q: What if I find a vulnerability and report it?
A: If you accessed without permission, you still committed a crime – even if you reported it. Always get permission FIRST.

Q: Can I use this on bug bounty programs?
A: Yes, but ONLY within the program's scope and rules. Never go beyond what's allowed.

Q: I'm under 18 – does the law apply to me?
A: YES. Minors can be prosecuted, though penalties may differ. Schools can also expel students for hacking.

